He took this word from the Gauls themselves and used it to distinguish between those he had conquered (the Gauls) and those he had not. While the origin is uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar noted: "Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (the Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles." (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others claim the meaning comes from the spear that they used in warfare, known as a ger (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word garim meaning "to shout," which indicated that the Germans were loud or noisy. (Names of Germany)

The early Roman historian Tacitus recorded in his AD 98 writing "De Origine et situ Germanorum," which told of the origins of the Germans, that "I should regard them as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were their home?" (Tacitus, 98)

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, not yet at least. They would send out their conquests to the lands of Germania for goods, and lead the occasional land campaign but in the end they mostly returned back home to their sprawling empire. So as the Germanic tribes began appearing in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire and traded their goods taken from the land, and their skills by serving within the ranks of the Roman army. (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17.)

I looked down, my mind blankly taking in the view before me. Unemotionally and silently, my practiced awareness studied the object, refusing to connect it to any abstract understanding. Thoughts flowed in and out of my mind almost faster than they appeared. My consciousness was so fluid that it seemed I had no thoughts of my own; I was simply experiencing what I saw. Once, following advice from an artist I worked with, I bought a book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." I had wanted to learn how to draw since I was six, and this book teaches everything from understanding a pencil to how the brain interprets lines. One technique it teaches is to frame a picture with a square, transforming a complex scene into a simple one. At the time, staring at a bowl of fruit in front of me, I couldn't mentally frame the picture. I was too overwhelmed and awed to do anything but stare in wonder. Picasso had his blue phase, Monet loved greenery, the Italian Renaissance masters displayed a rainbow of colors. If I had any pretensions of being an artist, this was the beginning of my piece, "Work in Brown." My fingers touched the brush, muscles tensed and relaxed as my hand moved through space, giving shape to my creative vision. Water swirled, calm and smooth. Matter broke away, carried into nothingness. My second attempt was more anxious, my hand smacking the brush against the wall. The offensive brown package refused to budge, stuck like a slug. With a mop in hand, I frowned at the rude bundle of processed animal and plant matter left as a message for the bathroom cleaners at Rite Aid. A few more flushes, a few more moments of inner reflection, and my hand reached for the toilet paper, wrapping itself around the handle until it resembled an oven mitt. Standing straight, then bending, my hand slowly dipped into the bowl, like a mother preparing a Thanksgiving turkey for the oven.

Teenagers are dying behind the wheel. Several factors come together to create this deadly vector of statistics for the youngest American drivers. The National Institutes of Health explain that one aspect of the problem is that the teen brain is literally not ready for the hazards of driving. Simple inexperience also lies at the heart of the problem. This inexperience not only causes more fatal accidents, but also a higher rate of vehicle rollover, speeding, and driving off the road.
Teens also fare far worse when they travel with their peers—which anyone with an iota of sense knows they do on a regular basis. The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center conducted a study that showed the following correlation: between the age of the passenger and the number of traffic accidents occurring.
California and other states have attempted to increase the safety of teen drivers by requiring temporary provisional licenses that limit the hours that teens may drive and prohibit other minors as passengers.
But provisional driver’s licenses are, in my opinion, stopgap measures. The real issue is that—as a group—the youngest drivers are, by all statistical markers, simply not able to adequately handle the risks and responsibilities. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman believes even 18 is too young for a regular driver’s license. USA Today reports that Zuckerman has performed research suggesting a common desire among those under the age of 19-20 to take risks for the sheer thrill of the sensation. It makes sense then, to delay driving at least until the tendency to thrill-seek has begun to level out. If we continue to issue driver’s licenses to young teens, we will not only continue to see deadly accidents happening, but the death toll is likely to reach staggering proportions in the next few years. By 2010, the Baby-Boomer’s babies will be eligible to drive and millions of new teen drivers will ready to hit the road.
Legislation dealing with this issue would be reasonably straightforward. Schools could continue to provide driver’s education classes to begin the learning process for future drivers, but no one under the age of 18 could operate a motor vehicle. A provisional permit could still be issued prior to granting a full driver’s license, and a certain number of practical driver’s training hours would still be required as well. The specific number of hours required could be based on the number of hours already required by the majority of states (in California, for example, that number is currently 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of practice with an adult.) Because the deadly statistics for teen drivers come from a cross-section of all states, uniform, national legislation on this issue would be a reasonable—and I believe effective—means of protecting teens across the nation.
The legislation I suggest is by no means a novel idea.

After exploring the Library of Congress's collection of early Edison films, I decided to watch all the trick films, which numbered fifteen from 1895 to 1901. These films generally employ creative editing to create illusions. My film study mainly focused on describing the poetics of the majority of trick films and examining the unique characteristics present in a few of the later films. On the turn of the century, trick films are confined to a stage, composed within a frontal proscenium, with no camera movement, using long and medium shots, and adhering to the strict one shot = one film methodology. However, some films from the early twentieth century dared to deviate from these guidelines by introducing elements like multiple shots.
One of the most noticeable aspects that trick films share is the filming of an interior set within the frame of a frontal proscenium. The camera does not move from its proscenium position to follow figures or objects. This composition was very common in early films and drew its roots from the theatre and, for trick films, vaudeville and magic acts. One limitation inherent in the use of the stage is that figures in trick films generally only move side-to-side, and do not walk towards or away from the camera. For instance, in the film Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), actors enter from the right side and move back and forth along the horizontal axis. Even as they exit the frame, the camera does not follow them.
The frontal proscenium style of composition also means that shots tend to be long shots and, more rarely, medium shots. Close-up shots are never used in any of the trick films from the Edison catalog. This borrows from the theatre and vaudeville tradition, where the audience would see the entire performance at any given time, framed by the borders of the stage. Similar to most early films, actors do not move from the middle ground towards the camera, so close-ups never occur.
Generally, most early trick films follow the pattern that one conceptual shot equals a film. This limits the length of most trick films to about a minute or less, depending on the frames per second used. It also limits the dramatic or narrative usage of the trick films; most of them focus on short vaudeville-style tricks, such as magic, disappearing, and switching acts with little story. However, note that in a trick film, one conceptual shot in the viewer’s eyes does not actually equal one physical shot. A single “shot” may actually be several joined together to produce the illusion of apparition or disappearing. Look carefully at The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), one of the earlier trick films. A closer inspection reveals the moment where the physical shot with Mary’s severed “head” begins, even though the whole film is conceptually one shot to the viewer.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early and ardent proponent of Republicanism. Although he was primarily an agriculturalist, his professional background and brief political career made him known for his dedication and outspokenness in matters of personal freedom and government. His commitment to an agrarian system underpinned almost all of his views on government. It was his endeavor to preserve and promote what he considered the most superior of all professions that influenced his arguments on sovereignty, constitutionality, and even the judiciary system.

John Taylor believed that the United States had a great opportunity to establish an ideal system because there was no native tradition to impede the founders of the government, allowing for the establishment of self-government. He strongly believed in the interdependence of natural human rights, asserting that if one is denied, all will fail, and the value of those remaining is diminished. These rights should therefore be beyond the reach of the government. He claimed that what some called the "state of nature" meant that those with physical prowess and malevolent intelligence would profit, but in civilization, this should not be the case.

To create this ideal society, Taylor believed that a government must account for the inherent good and evil within man. Taylor was very rigid in his views on a dualistic morality. He claimed, "Since government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human" (Ibid., pg. 167). He defined good principles as those that protect private property, improve agriculture, and discourage capitalism, and believed that a government founded on good principles would function equitably regardless of its administration, which would inevitably be led by avarice and self-interest. He believed that self-interest was man's motivation in all things, but that it was only considered evil when it led beyond the creation of a society based on the public good to sub-societies that lived at the expense of others. A good government was necessary to restrain man's natural evil, and even then it must be under careful observation to avoid the addition of bad principles.

Taylor, like many other staunch Republicans of his time, called for a strict construction of the Constitution. He wanted an extremely limited Federal government, with no more rights or powers allowed to it than were explicitly stated in the Constitution. He understood that an extensive Federal government was expensive and therefore likely to be despotic. However, he believed that a simple, literal interpretation was dangerous, and that without reference to the intent of the writers, such a method could easily become corrupt. Even more, he considered the Declaration of Independence the true charter of the United States, because it more explicitly describes the country as a group of sovereign states rather than one nation.

In Figure 17, there was a significant decrease in commuter log submissions during the third month of the project. This was somewhat disappointing, and the reason for this drop is unclear. The onset of winter in a New England campus likely contributed to the decrease in bicycle and pedestrian commuters. Additionally, December marks the end of the fall semester, during which time everyone is busy with schoolwork and grading, potentially causing the commuter log to slip off the radar. Furthermore, December brings the holiday season, leading to a month-long break for students and faculty, during which many do not need to come to campus. Classes resume in late January, which might also explain the low number of logs for that month. However, February's low submission count remains unexplained. It's possible that projects like this initially experience a surge of enthusiasm that naturally decreases over time. To counteract this trend, we implemented the Carpool Challenge Week in March, a special campaign to boost participation, which did lead to an increase in log submissions. The key challenge was to maintain project momentum despite natural decreases in engagement and the added difficulty of holiday and semester breaks in higher education.

Another challenge for this project, or any alternative commuting project, is the deeply ingrained cultural preference for driving cars. To encourage alternative commuting modes, we provided various prize incentives, including gift certificates to local restaurants, coffee shops, massage therapists, an independent bookstore, and national chain stores. It would have been interesting to see how larger prizes, such as bicycles, hybrid cars, or electric cars, could have influenced participation. The value of these prizes remained constant throughout the project. If the prizes had increased in value over time, it might have helped to sustain engagement. While the initial gift cards were sufficient, announcing additional prizes like bicycles in December and hybrid or electric cars in January could have likely increased participation and engagement.

An ETF, or exchange-traded fund, is a type of security that tracks an index, commodity, or basket of assets similarly to an index fund, but with the flexibility and tradability of a stock on an exchange. ETFs offer the diversification of index funds along with the advantages of single stock ownership, such as the ability to short sell, buy on margin, and purchase as few as one share per transaction. Despite these advantages, ETFs typically have lower expense ratios than mutual funds. However, they still require payment of commissions for trades, similar to stock orders. Another advantage of ETFs is the wide variety of funds available. While these benefits are clearly stated, it is essential for informed investors to evaluate whether these benefits, such as diversification, genuinely exist and to what extent. For this analysis, we will examine the ETF IHF and compare it against its top 10 holdings to determine if the benefits of owning a single ETF match those of a diversified portfolio of the ten stocks, and whether there are better configurations of these stocks that could provide a more optimized Sharpe ratio or return.

To evaluate the ETF, including all holdings would be impractical, so we will only consider the top 10 holdings, which account for 63.58% of the ETF's assets. Below are the top 10 holdings and their respective percentages of total assets.

To estimate how well these ten stocks represent the ETF IHF, we will use the current percentage of assets, normalized to 100%, to calculate the contributions of each stock to a portfolio's Beta and return if the portfolio were composed entirely of these 10 stocks in the proportions set by the ETF's holdings. The calculations for Beta and return are included in the chart below.

From the chart, it is clear that the return of a portfolio consisting of only the top 10 holdings is 6.11% higher than the ETF, representing a 16% increase in returns. Additionally, the Beta of the top ten holdings is 0.12 lower than the ETF as a whole. These results suggest that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could offer higher returns with a lower Beta. However, it is possible that the means of these two portfolios may not differ statistically.

To determine if these portfolios are indeed statistically different, we will calculate the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and normalize it to 100% to compare their accumulated standard deviation to that of the ETF IHF.

Dream-land is one of Edgar Allan Poe’s self-proclaimed better poems. In “Dream-Land” Poe uses the term “Thulé” in lines 6 and 56 which Mabbott traces back to Virgil. Virgil used the term in reference to an island north of Britain which the Greeks considered the edge of the known world. It is certain that Virgil did use the term however there is a more current source to which some credit must be given. Poe was very interested in German authors. This quote is important because it shows Poe’s familiarity with Gothe’s writing. Karl J. Arndt, in his book Poe’s Politian and Goethe’s Mignon, comments on the similarity of their two poems drawing the conclusion that Poe was imitating Goethe. Oxford Companion to English Literature says of Gothe was a celebrated writer of the poetic drama Faust which was published in two parts the first in 1808 and the second in the year of Gothe’s death 1832. Within the poetic verse of Faust’s second part lies a short poem titled “The King of Thulé”. The poem is about a king whose wife dies after she gives him the gift of a goblet. After his wife passes he begins drinking heavily and crying from the memory of his dead queen. He then decides it is his time to die and gives his possessions to his children save for the goblet. He then walks to a cliff, throws the goblet into the ocean, closes his eyes, and dies. The demeanor of the King of Thule and the description of the king in Dream-Land are very similar, maybe a dark doppelganger of Poe’s loss and crutch of drinking. Faust was also composed into a romantic drama by H P Grattan in 1842, which was less than one year prior to Poe’s use of the term Thule in “The Pit and the Pendulum”. Poe references Thule twice in his collected writings. Once Poe references “ultma Thule” in The Pit and the Pendulum but he uses this phrase in “Dream-Land” twice, as book ends for the poem. “The King of Thule” and “Dream-Land” can be read as companion pieces. In “Dream-Land” the speaker says. He then describes the landscape of Thule and how it is dark, lonely, he is haunted by dead friends, and he sees a shaded world without color. All of these scenes would be read into “The King of Thule” by Gothe as he has just lost his wife, he is lonely, and he has lost his will to rule or even live. The entire poem is a description as though the speaker has stepped into Goethe’s poem. Gothe was a significant author who Poe would have known if for no other reason then his respect for Tennyson. Poe had this to say when asked if he admired Tennyson. Aside from the connection to Tennyson Poe would have been exposed to Gothe’s work in the many reproductions that were taking place after the original publication.

Under California law, a customer who was injured after slipping and falling on an applesauce spill in a supermarket could be awarded punitive damages if they can show that the store manager acted with malice, as he was informed twice about the spill but failed to clean it for half an hour because he was eating dinner.

A judge is unlikely to dismiss Jennifer Palmer’s claim for punitive damages outright. To justify an award of punitive damages, a plaintiff must present evidence that the defendant’s actions were committed with a willful and conscious disregard for the probable harm that would result from the conduct, and that the conduct was despicable. Palmer can argue that Martin should have known about the potential harm of not cleaning a spill because multiple D&D customers were injured in slips in the months before Palmer’s accident, and despite this, he still failed to clean the spill. While her argument that Martin’s actions were despicable is less convincing, it is still reasonable given that six slip-and-fall incidents occurred in 2009 and Martin still did not take appropriate action to ensure the store’s safety.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, Rich Wayne, an employee of D&D Markets, informed his manager, Paul Martin, about an applesauce spill in an aisle. Martin told Wayne that he was on a dinner break and “didn’t have time to deal with customer complaints.” At 5:15 pm, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also reported the spill to Mr. Martin, and he responded similarly. At 5:30 pm, Jennifer Palmer, the plaintiff, slipped and fell on the spill and sustained a serious back injury. Before Palmer’s accident, five different slip-and-fall incidents had been reported at D&D’s in 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for compensatory and punitive damages related to her injury, and we are considering whether to file a motion for partial summary against the punitive damage claim.

In California, a plaintiff can recover punitive damages for a breach of an obligation not arising out of a contract if the defendant acted with “oppression, fraud, or malice.” Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010). The statute defines malice as conduct that intended to cause harm, or absent intent, the conduct must be “despicable” and committed with “a willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others.” id. at § (c)(1). Courts have characterized conduct as malicious when committed with a conscious disregard of the plaintiff’s rights when the defendant “was aware of the probable dangerous consequences of his conduct, and that he willfully and deliberately failed to avoid those consequences.” Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

Almost four years ago I took a course in Islam at CBC. The main topic of heated discussion in the class was whether or not Islam is a hostile religion. I believe that the question is even more relevant today than ever before. Looking back on the events since 9/11, I have personally observed mass media shift from a hostile view of Islam and extremists to an extreme form of tolerance for Islam in America. I don’t think in 2001 we could have ever had a presidential candidate with the name Barack Obama, who has an obvious Muslim background in his family.
The Biography of the Prophet fascinates me because, according to what I know of the history of Muhammad, the biography contradicts the personality of Muhammad. From what I know and learned in the past, I thought Muhammad forced converts to Islam. He would conquer and take over tribes and then force them to adopt the Islamic religion. However, according to the biography, Muhammad was written as a sort of martyr, who was misunderstood and even humbled himself to others. After which, one by one people came to see the truth in his teachings and sought him out.
Additionally, there are uncanny similarities between the ministries of Jesus and the ‘miracles’ of Muhammad. The most obvious is when he took mutton and milk and multiplied it so that there was more than enough for forty men. It is this style of writing that makes me believe the writers wanted Muhammad to be perceived as the humble prophet, who needed not to prove anything, but simply lived in truth and miracles. This sort of fallacy is the worst because it downplays the miracle and life of Jesus Christ. To me, it is like they are stealing and trying to take credit for the life and personhood of Jesus through Muhammad.
There are also many stories in the biography that make it seem like part of their agenda is to provide proof of ‘witness’ or of how people ‘on their own’ converted to Islam. But the problem is that a lot of the stories are at least from a third-party perspective. That is, the author illustrates that he heard from so-and-so who heard from so-and-so, etc. I didn’t like this much because although their idea was that it provided proof of the truth of the stories, I thought it diminished the stories and made it seem all that more suspicious.
I think the thing that bothers me most about this work is that they try and exalt and lift up Muhammad as a godly man who was humble, endearing, wise, and gentle. But history contradicts the idea that Muhammad was a gentle and humble man, and I can’t help but think if Muslims today know the true history behind Muhammad’s rise to power.

The teachings of Jesus and his beliefs during his lifetime were immediately left behind in the development of Christian thought that moved forward after his life. If we look at this history in broad strokes, we see a trend of Christianity straying farther and farther from its origin. It seems that today’s world shows an ever-growing awareness and an unprecedented progressive tendency. While traditional people remain and will resist any kind of thinking beyond what was taught to them, this portion of the population may not be prominent enough to influence the whole. Among Christians, a historical awareness will grow immensely in future years. A yearning will spread to distinguish the doctrines that were added into Christianity over time from the actual intent of the religion’s namesake. It may take decades or even centuries, but the outcome will be inevitable: There will be a great reversal in the trend of Christian history. There will be a progression back to its original form. A movement will grow in numbers that will remove layers of doctrine, one after the other, just as if the clock started moving backward, until nothing is left except a conception of what Jesus introduced to humanity on behalf of God, before any other thinkers made such claims. When this trend sweeps through the United States and Europe, influencing masses in its wake to worship as if we were living at the time of Jesus, following only his ideas, the church as an institution will remain strong to lead the way. However, because the theological clock will have moved backward, the extreme proliferation of diversity in Christendom will reverse into more and more uniformity of belief and practice. Between regions, between denominations, between divisions of every kind, we will see instead of differences, increasing similarities. Human history is filled with great reversions. Just one example is how Christians were at one time persecuted, shunned and killed by the Roman Empire. But later that empire became a Christian institution. Our country has gone from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The great reversion coming in our future will play itself out in the arena of the Christian religion, undoing history in search of the source, and undoing diversity in the process. It is crucial to note that part of what will make this process possible will be a method of reading Jesus’ words as metaphorical, and not as literal statements. So what is it that happened since Jesus’ lifetime? If we look far enough back into history, we find only Judaism, the theological beginning for the Christian religion. Monotheism, the perception of a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures, were all at the core of the religion by the time the Romans assumed control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish population did not share one spirit. They divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots and a majority of common people.

I believe that The Jungle demonstrates how people inherently are greedy and self-centered. They only want to improve their own lives and never care for those below them. The Jungle shows this in many ways, especially through the owners and managers of large factories. They only want to make their companies and factories as big as possible. They do not care about anyone or anything that gets in their way or is harmed by their progress. In Upton Sinclair's words, "The buildings stood stark and black against the sky; here and there from the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." Sinclair paints a picture of the immense damage caused by this pollution. He shows that the owners have no regard for any person or animal that might be harmed. They do not care about the massive plumes of smoke billowing from the factories or the animal waste and runoff from the thousands of pens around Packingtown. The owners and managers also did not care about their employees working to make them rich. They would do anything to maximize or save every dollar, as Sinclair writes, "From top to bottom, the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere; there is no place in it where a man is worth more than a dollar." They forced their employees to work long hours and then, without warning, could lay off thousands of people at once with no compensation or help finding a job. During the period when The Jungle is set, there were few, if any, laws or regulations protecting workers' safety and well-being, allowing managers and owners to act freely and force employees to work faster and in terrible conditions. Although the book does not state it directly, those who lived and worked themselves to death in Packingtown were expected to endure the horrible conditions both while working in the factories and living around them. There were no agencies or organizations set up to provide information or help to workers. Unions were formed, but they often did more harm than good as they profited from the poor workers. The workers were so badly treated and had no way to escape the system of Packingtown that they were described as slaves, as Sinclair writes, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Many authors adopt various methods to evoke specific feelings or attitudes in their readers about important themes. Some techniques are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald employs a multitude of these strategies in his novel The Great Gatsby. Occasionally, he pairs an adjective with a noun that typically wouldn’t be paired in that way to create a certain atmosphere around a subject. At other times, he assigns meaning to a symbol and then employs it for the same purpose. Fitzgerald uses this latter technique with numerous colors, including gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. In The Great Gatsby, he constructs a significance for white/gray and red/pink, then later utilizes that meaning to remind readers of feelings associated with important objects.

Fitzgerald associates white/gray with uniformity, with white conveying a sense of refinement and higher class, and gray signifying age and fadedness. He establishes this significance at the beginning of the novel by repeatedly using both colors. Daisy and Jordan are consistently depicted as “in white” (8); in fact, everyone wears white: Nick in “white flannels” (41) at Gatsby’s party, Tom in a “white shirt” (36) when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine as “powdered milky white” (30). The only time people do not wear white is when Nick observes Gatsby’s party: “the halls… are gaudy with primary colors” (40). Fitzgerald further emphasizes these colors by coloring many mundane, unimportant subjects with them: Nick’s commute to work takes him “down the white chasms of lower New York” (56), the names of people at Gatsby’s parties are now “gray names” (61) in Nick’s timetable, Catherine’s apartment is “one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses”—uniformity (28). He also describes ordinary people or places as white or gray: Jordan and Daisy had a “white girlhood” (19) together, there are “gray cars” and “gray land” (23) in the valley of ashes, the “Italian child” in the railroad is “gray” (26), and the dog-seller is “a gray old man” (27).

After investing enough meaning in white/gray, Fitzgerald uses them to signify unimportance or uniformity for certain subjects. This use of color to convey meaning to readers begins with Daisy. After a period of little significant use of either color, Fitzgerald describes Daisy as “dressed in white” in a “little white roadster”; readers start to see Daisy as less of a character and more like a uniform addition, something Gatsby desires and yearns for (74). Fitzgerald employs this technique around Daisy to reinforce the impression of her being a more uniform addition, for example, with a “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar” (18), and she is once again in a “white” (115) dress before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter.

San Diego County is extremely productive in agriculture due to its mild, sunny climate. Common crops grown here include: tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits such as peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a strong demand for organic community-supported agriculture in the San Diego area, with many local organizations experiencing long waiting lists for their products. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Many organic farms offer tours of their operations and allow public access for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. This type of operation can help landowners gain access to government programs while improving habitat, allowing for recreational use and offering opportunities for farm tours and other educational programs.

Culture plays a significant role in any negotiation. Culture is not homogenous, nor is it a specific thing. It is also not singular or uniform. Cultural generalizations, while appropriate, are not enough for a negotiator. It is more productive to understand the significance of a culture to the matter at hand and how the culture's attitude will influence the negotiations. When approaching a foreign culture, it is easier to understand it in relation to one's own culture, which inevitably leads to comparisons. Understanding a foreign culture or mindset can involve studying its history or realizing its prejudices. Rather than judging or attempting to change a culture, one should accept it as it is and work within its boundaries, especially in the context of negotiation, and especially if one is at a weaker bargaining position. If a negotiator finds themselves on "away" territory, respect for traditions and beliefs can only help in overcoming cultural barriers and moving the negotiation forward.

“The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” This is first seen in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible and is also found at the outset of St. Anselm's argument regarding the existence of God. This belief seems to be shared by the other author we will be discussing, Thomas Aquinas. Since both arguments are in defense of the same concept, and our challenge is to determine which one is better, we must, for the sake of brevity, begin with the presumption that they are both correct in their belief in the existence of God, specifically the God of the Bible. Allowing for a God-type figure that does not resemble the one our two authors believe in would not permit us to appropriately compare their arguments, as they are essentially in defense of one specific concept of God. That being said, I would suggest that while each of them brings up valid points, neither truly provides a comprehensive basis for belief in God.

Sometimes in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince who would later be known as Buddha was born. Throughout his life, he renounced his worldly pursuits and attained enlightenment, and his teachings laid the foundation for Buddhism, the most orthodox sect of which is known as Theravada Buddhism. This religion, which is approximately twenty-five hundred years old, has evolved significantly over time, as seen in the Theravada-majority nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Both monks and laypeople participate in this ceremony, which holds religious significance despite its lack of mention in Buddha's teachings. These changes range from superficial traditions to the religion's core soteriological principles. The Theravada Buddhist community, from both monastic and lay perspectives, has had to adapt its doctrinal principles over time due to various external and internal influences, both hostile and benign.

There are several key terms used in this discussion. Internal forces are those originating from within the Buddhist community, regardless of monastic status, while external forces are from non-Buddhists. Hostile forces are those that harm or intend to harm the Buddhist community due to a negative perception of Buddhism, and benign forces do not intend to harm or help the community but may do so incidentally. These terms will reappear throughout the discussion.

First, it's essential to examine the fundamental beliefs of the religion: the doctrines at the core of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the Triple Gem of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma encompasses the Tripitaka, or the three baskets, of Buddhist texts: the Sutta Pitaka, which contains all the Suttas; the Vinaya Pitaka, which includes the disciplinary rules; and the Abhidhamma Pitaka, which covers the metaphysical components of Buddhism. Metaphysical concepts like Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (inherent suffering), and Anicca (impermanence) must be understood to escape Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth. Along with ending Sansara, one can also conquer lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion). The Vinaya Pitaka outlines rules for both laypeople and monks. Laypeople have five precepts: I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not engage in improper sexual conduct, and I shall not use intoxicating substances. Monks have many more rules to follow. The most fundamental doctrine in Buddhism is the Four Noble Truths, which state that life is suffering (Dukkha), that attachment causes suffering, that suffering can be overcome.

The United States and Mexico had a long-standing rivalry that lasted for 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. The most intense conflict was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, in which the United States defeated Mexico and gained Texas and the American Southwest as new territories. There were numerous other disputes between the two nations, which faded away before World War I. The rivalry started due to disagreements over key issues such as religion, culture, and traditions, as well as conflicting economic interests (Diehl and Goerts, 2000, p. 145).

This pattern is common among neighboring nations. Countries sharing a border often have conflicting interests that lead to rivalries. The United States and Mexico are not unique in this regard. David M. Pletcher (1977) stated, “Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems” (p. 41). Indeed, these two nations are geographically close to the United States and have historically been rivals, while many other Latin American countries have maintained good relations with the United States.

Religious differences were a significant factor in the tension between the United States and Mexico, a problem that has affected many nations throughout history. Sally Frahm (2001) noted, “If in the twentieth century Americans opposed fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries they opposed Catholicism and monarchy” (p. 86). The Cold War between the United States and the Soviet Union was a mix of ideological struggle and competition over vital interests. In this case, the ideological differences were about religious preferences rather than political structure. This mistrust between the Americans and Mexicans can be traced back to the animosity between the English and Spanish, a legacy from their colonial rulers, which became a major obstacle in establishing friendly diplomatic relations.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) identified 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States during their 57-year rivalry. Most of these disputes were territorial issues, such as border raids from Mexican territory into Mexico and other frontier problems. Border raids by outlaws from American towns were a major issue that persisted until both nations exerted military control over their borders (Schmitt, 1974, p. 97).

Schmitt (1974) explains that the rivalry began to abate as Mexico became increasingly dependent on the United States and finally ended as American ambitions shifted from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico during the latter half of the 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, I suddenly and unexpectedly became disabled by an illness I never knew existed.

I was a nurse at the time. I chose this profession because of a deep-seated need for the safety and security I didn't have as a child. "You'll always be able to find work; people will always get sick." was the mantra I heard over and over as I grew into adolescence and beyond. So—even though my dream was to be a scientist or a journalist, preferably both, I chose nursing.

Nevertheless, here I am: forty-six years old and single, no money to speak of, and unable to work. To this day, I am disabled, and after fifteen years of living on Social Security Disability, I have literally nothing left that I can call "mine." I get by, but every day is a struggle and an assault on my security, safety, and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore, yet there is one thing that I know to be true. I could not have made it through these years without the help of my family and a few good friends, no matter how strong I was. And believe me, when real disaster strikes, you do not feel very strong at all.

My point is that there will always be emergencies in life—big and small. There are no guarantees, and no matter how well one prepares, some things are just too big to overcome on your own.

I agree wholeheartedly that we in the U.S. need to stop putting all of our eggs in big government's "basket"; Lord knows it is moldy and falling apart, anyway. Yet I would much rather see Americans learning to trust one another again—learning to help each other and to ask for help, rather than each of us individually scrambling out to the backyard to build fallout shelters.

The Conservatives in the US talk about the "rugged individualism" that built this country; but in truth, what kept our forefathers going in hard times wasn't rugged individualism, it was compassion, mutual respect, and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast by going it alone.

So, by all means, be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit; first aid supplies, water purifying tablets, and plastic sheeting and duct tape for the windows in the event of a biological attack. I have several flashlights and all sorts of batteries, lots and lots of candles and waterproof matches, and canned goods, too. If you have the land and the resources for a small farm and the ability to can or preserve your own food—do it. It's a great idea, as is a wood stove, as long as you do not live in an apartment.

But while you are at it, get to know your neighbors.

Why do organisms evolve in the manner that they do? Are there restrictions or constraints that influence the direction of evolutionary change? Although in 1917 D’Arcy Thompson stated that "Even now the zoologist has scarce begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms," the same can be said today. More recently, mathematical modeling has been applied to general aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis through both ontogeny and phylogeny (e.g., Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our study is exploring how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic change in Prunum, in combination with experimental studies, can be used to elucidate the mechanisms involved in the direction and magnitude of evolutionary-developmental change. We used X-radiographic images of Prunum species to delineate quantitative parameters that could in turn be used to model hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies. These parameters were entered into the software program CerioShell (Stone, 1995). We modeled hypothetical shell morphologies that could be used to interpret the boundaries of possible morphological change in Prunum. These results are being combined with experimental and descriptive studies in order to better understand macroevolutionary events in this clade.

A shell can be thought of as a structure that is a tube that travels over time through 360 degrees of space. These revolutions or turns of a coiled shell are called whorls, which are considered to spiral around an imaginary central axis. This axis runs through the central column of the shell and is known as the columella. The speed at which the whorls enlarge can vary, and a continuous line separates each whorl and is referred to as a suture. In most shells, the largest whorl of a shell is the last whorl (body whorl). The spire is considered to be all the whorls except the last. The apex is the tip of the spire and the opposite end is referred to as the base. The animal extends out of its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed in apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural views. (The "usual" orientation of a shell is an apertural view, with the aperture toward the viewer and with the apex pointing up.)

A method for counting whorls is seen below. First, the shell should be viewed from the apical view and then it should be determined where the first suture begins. A line can be then drawn dividing the shell into two parts. Whorls are counted from this line, and are estimated to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be viewed as a series of apertures that travel through time and space as the animal accretes (i.e., builds) its shell. It is possible to trace the path of the aperture via coordinates of the center of each whorl’s aperture as well as the horizontal and vertical radius of the aperture.

This trajectory can be graphically and mathematically represented. Once a mathematical formulation is made, it is then possible to vary parameters and modify the mollusk’s skeletogenesis.

Indonesia's neonatal and infant mortality rates have remained largely unchanged over the past decade. While the country is progressing toward many of the Millennium Development Goals, such as water and sanitation targets, the improvements in child and maternal health are way below what is needed to meet the goals by 2015. Below are several reasons for these shortcomings, suggesting the need to bolster the healthcare system rather than just focus on programmatic interventions.

Indonesia has made progress in the percentage of births attended by skilled healthcare workers, with 72% now meeting this target. However, this includes traditional workers like midwives who cannot manage complicated pregnancies, leading to a significant number of maternal deaths from hemorrhage. Thus, while the indicator has improved, there is still much work to be done. Furthermore, there has been a decline in the proportion of diarrheal cases in children under five years treated by healthcare professionals. Postnatal care data is incomplete but indicates low rates nationwide.

Cesarean-section rates remain low, at around 4%. They also highlight another issue: while urban areas have a 7% c-section rate, rural areas have a 2% rate, indicating a lack of healthcare equity. Access to healthcare services is concentrated in urban areas, and there's a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles, suggesting that the poor have much more difficulty accessing healthcare, likely due to out-of-pocket costs.

Considering the next steps for improving neonatal and maternal care indicators, the first question is how to most effectively address the lack of healthcare services. Should Indonesia focus on program-specific approaches or strengthen the overall healthcare system without focusing on pre- and postnatal care for mothers and children? Programmatic approaches have clear advantages—they have well-defined, manageable objectives and can generate faster results. However, there are considerations to keep in mind. One major concern is that investing heavily in a particular area can lead to reduced funding and resources for other sectors, with human resources being drawn to areas with more funding. Moreover, running multiple parallel programs can result in service duplication and uncoordinated efforts, leading to increased paperwork and administrative burdens.

Victorian novels are distinguished by their meticulous attention to detail and focus on the aristocracy of the period. Two novels that are considered Victorian but deviate from this tradition are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. Both novels incorporate an element of mystery and a flair for the bizarre, which is atypical of the period's novels, thereby enhancing the characters within each work; offering insights into their motives and emotions.

“Suddenly, a multitude of bewildering and confusing thoughts crowded his mind. He seemed to still be walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were angrily disputing: for the very words they said sounded in his ears; and when he tried to focus his attention, … he found that he was talking to them…. Suddenly, he started at the report of firearms; and there rose into the air loud cries and shouts; lights gleamed before his eyes, and all was noise and confusion, as some unseen hand bore him hurriedly away. Through all these rapid visions, there ran an undefined, uneasy consciousness of pain, which wore and tormented him incessantly.”

The two novels employ this mystery often through dream sequences or dreamlike states, though the content and function vary in each specific case. In Oliver Twist, these strange events often reveal insights into Oliver’s inner layers, what pains him, and his awareness about the true nature of the things happening around him. When the shooting of Oliver is revisited in chapter 28, Oliver relives the shooting vividly, as if in a dream, while he struggles to find help. The passage emphasizes the lack of control Oliver had over the events that unfolded, as well as the dire straights his health had come to occupy, which were strongly present through Oliver’s hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting itself overwhelmed him, all his senses were numbed as he did not notice the “unseen hand” that bore him away; he experienced his despair over again removed from the shock of pain, as the pain is now constant and is linked with fear rather than surprise. With Oliver being overwhelmed, the question arises about whose will brought about his misfortune, because it was certainly not his own. This shooting reinforces the notion that Oliver had little control over anything, as he could not bring himself to even attempt to gain control of an event’s outcome, even while his life was in danger. A growing sense of defeat in Oliver is also implied by this selection, as if old Fagin had begun to break him, forcing him into accepting this despair, influencing his ability to react. Otherwise, it can be assumed that Oliver would have made some effort, at least simply for the sake of his own life.

“The day passed off – day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as it came – and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in its dreadful silence and short in its fleeting hours.”

A couple of years ago, I worked at an after-school program tutoring elementary-aged students. While I tried my best to help them with any subjects they were struggling in, my strengths were in English and reading. One of the instructors recruited me to help a little boy named Adrian (I believe he was in third or fourth grade) who was having a lot of trouble reading. It soon became apparent that something was wrong; he had the most peculiar problems. Some letters he could pronounce perfectly, while others he couldn't even come close to. It was the strangest thing. He was of Latino descent, and although he spoke perfect English, it seemed like he didn't know the English alphabet very well. We struggled with this until I met his mother. I was babysitting the remaining students while the rest of the after-school group was on a field trip when his mother walked in. She didn't speak a word of English, only Spanish. With my limited knowledge of Spanish, we managed to communicate, but it was then that it hit me: Adrian could read fine, but he just didn't know the English alphabet well. I don't know if that revelation helped him much, but I hope he's doing better now.

I tell this story to address the problem of language barriers in schools, especially in California. I also tell it to prove that it's not always as obvious as we'd think. Even a child who speaks perfect English can still have trouble reading. I believe everyone can agree that this problem exists, so what can we do? In Adrian's case, the solution was fairly simple: tutoring in English, particularly the alphabet and pronunciations. However, for many children who barely speak English, the solution is much more complex. There's no one-size-fits-all answer. The dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes—none of these things, by itself, will fix the problem. The key is to combine all of these approaches!

First of all, the dual language system is a great idea. Not just for children whose first language is Spanish, but for all children. "Children in two-way bilingual education programs have been found to outperform their peers academically." A lot of fear surrounds this idea, that it's a waste of resources and that the majority of children in schools will reap no benefit. But that's false. If we were to implement these sorts of programs in the classroom as the rule, rather than the exception, all children would benefit from it. How do we go about this, though? Do we require all teachers to be bilingual? No, that would be unreasonable and slightly unrealistic. However, I do think that having special aids, tutors, whatever you want to call them, who are bilingual would be beneficial.

From the time we are children, most of us are told that there is something out there that is larger than ourselves, beyond our comprehension. Some of us are sent to Sunday school to learn about it, while others go to temple or search within ourselves for answers. Many of us readily accept the religions passed down to us by our parents. However, some of us reject them wholeheartedly, denying the existence of anything beyond our individual egocentric universes. We may adopt one set of values only to later change our minds and embrace another. Whatever path we choose, we journey to define a part of ourselves through our unique perspectives on spirituality. We search for a light in the darkness to guide us out of the shadows and into the sunlight.

"A cardinal," my father said when I asked him what his favorite type of bird was. We sat on the front porch of our house, listening to the rain pound on the tin roof above us while we smoked our cigarettes together. The gutters channeled the rain, drowning the plants along the edge of the porch. He looked out into the rain, his gaze seemingly half searching, half reminiscing. He had grown thinner over the past few months, and his clothes hung loosely on his frame. His hair had thinned, sparser than I remembered it. He stared out into the rain still, avoiding eye contact. I felt alone, afraid, and unable to discuss with my father how much I would miss him because talking about it would only make it more real for both of us. I hugged him, sat back down, shifted my chair closer to his, and joined him in gazing out into the falling rain of the June twilight.

My father passed away in December of that year, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The chemotherapy and radiation did not ease my father's suffering but kept him alive a few more months beyond what the doctors had projected; whether this was of value when all he did was suffer longer I could not comprehend. What kind of God would do this, I thought to myself. Alone in the night, I said no prayers. If God existed, I believed, he had stopped listening to me long ago.

I did not want to witness my father's transition from this life to another. So I did not. I could not bear to watch the life that created me as it ended. I wanted to remember my father by how he lived, not how he died. Besides, I knew my father better than anyone else did, better than his family did, and I knew Dad would not want his only child to be a spectator at his death. I curled up in a ball in my bed for three days, waiting for the news.

No one even called me.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" is, in essence and in name, an "oxymoron for 'Old-New,'" as Ian Watt describes it in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. The Gothic mode has been criticized, praised, and accused of lacking real depth, but also lauded for its evocation of the 'terrible sublime' (Burke). The original "Gothic Novel," Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, employed the ideas of both "the ancient and the modern" romances to create the proto-Gothic genre and a new form of literary expression. Walpole used "old" theatrical elements and 'new' mimicry of nature in 'modern' novels to present what he called "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre incorporates many throwbacks to medieval Gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions. Even during the time of The Castle of Otranto's publication, the term "gothic" was used to describe many different peoples, styles, and time periods, often seen as archaic or unsophisticated in contrast to "modern" societal and literary advancements. The combination of the more theatrical "Gothic" and the new format of the novel (allowing the reader a more personal view of the characters' psychology) has kept Gothic relevant for such a long time, making it at once obsolete and fresh to readers distant from the original writing. One of the most prominent Gothic themes in Gothic novels is the concept of Chivalry. The medieval idea of chivalry, the process of training a proper knight, is both preserved and transformed in the original Gothic novel, The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry is important to Gothic writers because it represented the ideal of a brave, honorable, and competent knight, which they saw as lacking in their contemporary society. Through the use of chivalric concepts and manners, the "gothic past" becomes idealized and romanticized (hinting at the future evolution of Gothic to Romantic) and is used to attempt to improve the present. Walpole, when writing The Castle of Otranto, found himself in a politically tumultuous time and was despairing over the potential future. Immersed in politics and (arguably) unfair accusations, he may have begun to believe, even if not explicitly, that the supposed morality and innate "goodness" present in the Gothic era had somehow been lost in the society of his time. This is evident in several characters, one being Frederic. The reader can see before meeting Frederic that he embodies many chivalric traits, as he is described as: "The description of him includes a great many traditionally chivalric images; Frederic is, foremost, a prince, he has suffered, been suitably affected by tragedy that he leaves, and is currently supposed to have been killed by infidels. The figure of the 'gallant and courteous Knight' is, of course, exaggerated, bringing the soon to be Gothic trope of excess into play (66)."

Supply chain management is the sequence of processes involved in moving goods from the customer order to the raw materials stage, supply, production, and distribution of products to the customer. The term supply chain management was coined in 1982 by consultant Keith Oliver. Keith Oliver described the overall process of planning, implementing, and controlling what happens in the supply chain to satisfy customers' needs efficiently. There are six key elements to a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Managers use these six key elements to provide the best customer service.

Production is the first step in the supply chain process. Production is the foundation for the entire supply chain. The production stage outlines the when, why, where, and how everything will be produced. Managers need to understand what customers want. To know what customers want, managers can look at the market. The market is the biggest indicator of what customer demands are. Once managers have analyzed the market and understand customer demand, they are ready to decide what products should be produced and how many. After management has decided what to produce and how many, they are ready to decide where the products should be produced and at which plant would be best for volume and quality, keeping in mind customer demand and satisfaction must be met. After the production location has been decided, the next step is for managers to focus on scheduling workloads and maintenance of equipment. Production is a very important step in the supply chain process. Every detail is vital throughout the whole process. If every detail is not planned accordingly, it could cost the company a lot of time and money in the long run. For example, I used to work at Wal-Mart and Target retail stores. Both companies have a designed layout for every entity of the business, from the employee's uniform to receiving shipments from trucks. Having outlined processes allows a company to work smoothly without confusion about direction and expectations.

The second key element in supply chain management is supply. Supply is defined as the strategic decisions that should be made to determine the core capabilities of a facility and to foster outsourcing partnerships. A company may have many different divisions of production for a single product. All divisions consist of different equipment, workers, and specialties. The manager must decide which division is the best fit for the different processes of the product. Management may also decide to outsource the work to other companies. The core reason a manager would outsource the work is to create velocity. Velocity is the ability to provide quality and flexibility while at the same time reducing costs or maintaining low cost levels.

Hitler is alive in Myanmar, the sign reads.

Ellen Page, star of Juno, stands alone on a street corner with a piece of cardboard held above her head, the unsettling message scrawled with marker onto her sign. Myanmar, also known as Burma, is a Southeast Asian country ruled by a tyrannical military junta who seized power in 1962 through a coup d’état. In 2007, a wave of street protests erupted, the first public protests in a decade. Led by a large number of Burmese monks, these protests became known as the “Saffron Revolution,” so named for the color of the robes the monks wore. After the initial uprisings, the public became increasingly interested in the protests, and while the government initially allowed peaceful gatherings by the monks, violence soon escalated into what some saw as an all-out war between the monks and the military junta, with the military invading and looting monasteries across the country. Foreign journalists were detained and imprisoned on the spot, and a Japanese photojournalist named Kenji Nagai was killed on September 27, 2007, simply for being present at a street protest. Although the official death toll stands at 13, Colonel Hla Win, who defected from the army days before the official report, stated, “Many more people have been killed in recent days than you’ve heard. The bodies can be counted in several thousand.”

This is nothing new. While these are some of the most recent examples of atrocities taking place in our world, the desire of governments to suppress dissent and maintain complete control over their citizenry has been around for as long as civilization itself. Early Roman emperors declared themselves chosen by the gods to have complete executive rule over every aspect of their society. Japanese emperors are believed to be gods, sent to our world to lead their people to prosperity through the invention of Motorola cell phones and hara-kiri, and our current president, George W. Bush, has weekly conference calls with Ted Haggard, the leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a subsidiary group of the Republican Party.

Some of the most well-known examples of these actions include the 1989 June 4th protest at Tiananmen Square, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students gathered to protest the authoritarian rule of the government. The death toll in that incident varies widely, with official reports from the Chinese government stating between 200-300 dead to reports released by the Chinese Red Cross, which declared between 2,000-3,000 dead. Another example is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militias, aided by the Rwandan government, systematically killed all Tutsis, as well as political moderates, regardless of their ethnic backgrounds. Hitler’s ‘Third Reich,’ a period that spanned several years and several countries, saw anyone of Jewish background rounded up and killed, is another extreme example.

Duke Ellington's legacy in jazz significantly stems from his longevity and, consequently, his ability to develop his orchestra. Ellington's piano work is often understated in the selected compositions, yet as a composer, he excelled at creating complex pieces that highlighted the individual skills of his band members. He crafted a framework where soloists could freely improvise, and wrote tightly orchestrated pieces and phrases that showcased the unique styles of his band members. By doing this, he emphasized the overall tone of the orchestra, creating cohesive and original sounds for each piece. Ellington's mastery of individual players' sounds and how they fit together in a growing ensemble allowed him to write some of the most innovative and brilliant pieces in jazz history.

The Grove Music dictionary, discussing Ellington's sound and innovation, mentions "Creole Love Call" as an example of his use of voice as a jazz instrument throughout his career. This is an early example of Ellington's use of voice to add texture and color without lyrics. "Creole Love Call" also demonstrates his ability to complement the styles of his soloists, a trait evident throughout his career. This slow, deliberate twelve-bar blues piece contains six choruses, structured as follows:

Chorus 1: Call and response between voice and reeds, with the voice starting smoothly and melodically before transitioning to a rougher sound towards the end.
Chorus 2: Muted trumpet solo that elaborates on the basic melody and emphasizes extended blue notes.
Chorus 3: Sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, backed by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.
Chorus 4: Full band echoes the first chorus in a call and response by brass and reed sections.
Chorus 5: The climactic chorus, with reeds initiating the call and response in a high register, backed by syncopated stop-time from brass and rhythm sections.
Chorus 6: Returning to the structure of the first chorus, with call and response between voice and reeds. In this chorus, the voice采用“growl”技术Solo as an instrument.
Tag: A brief tag featuring a vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending by a trombone.

Ellington's use of voice to add a tone color dimension to this piece exemplifies a stylistic trait present throughout his work.

In "Hot and Bothered," recorded a year later, Ellington blends his skill in tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call and response phrase between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing uses the vocal elements of Miley's playing and instrumental aspects of Cox's voice to create a rich and complementary sound. "It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)" extends these ideas, as Ellington uses Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton, a key member of his orchestra, to great effect in introducing the melody on muted trombone.

She always felt like she needed something. This desire refused to be fulfilled. It began when she was 14, just entering puberty. And it was still there 3 years later, at the age of 17. Now, she had decided that she wanted someone rather than a thing. However, she had no interest in any boys. Some were drawn to her, but their attempts to woo the un-woo-able were awkward, and no one appealed to her. She often questioned herself about this strange notion, trying to figure out what could cause such a thing to happen to a teenage girl. The few years of contemplation brought up theories, but nothing was good enough for her to really guess. So she lived her life, continually questioning her desires.

A day at home was usually peaceful. Her parents were good and calm people. They never argued with each other, and surprisingly, arguments with their daughter were very rare. The only thing they ever argued about was her asserting her independence and free-spirited personality. She was the daughter of a very calm couple, but she definitely countered their energies with her lively and fun personality, which made her very likeable, combined with the fact that she was a nice person.

However, today was not a peaceful day. As she walked from room to room, trying to find some new inspiration for her life, she heard a short scream from the kitchen, the sound of her mother's beautiful voice. She ran into the room, starting to panic and frantically asked, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" She saw her mother lying on the ground, appearing to be in pain as she continually said "Ouch" in short breaths. The mother's daughter ran to her side and put a hand on her to try to help. "Ouch... sweetie, I... need you to take me to the hospital." The words were rushed and squeezed, and her daughter could tell she was in immense pain. "Okay Mom, just tell me where I can pick you up." Her mother directed her hands, and at this moment, the hero of the house was very grateful she had taken classes to strengthen herself. She carried her mother to the car, laid her down in the back seat, and drove.

A visit to the hospital brought a scent of disinfectant and sickness, mixed with fear. But she wasn't feeling that, as her mind was too occupied with helping her mother. She quickly brought the injured woman in and started calling for the doctors' help. A few worried faces gathered around, and someone quickly pulled up a gurney and laid her mother down on it. They took her away to be immediately checked, and her daughter was left to sit in worry.

Her mother had fallen off a step stool while trying to grab a vase from the highest cabinet they had.

This study aimed to demonstrate that adherence to a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), as indicated by a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score," is associated with a reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, as well as stroke-related mortality. The aMed diet is a modified version of the Med diet, characterized by increased consumption of plant foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (compared to saturated fats), and fish, while decreasing the intake of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol consumption is permitted.

Previous prospective studies have shown an inverse association between adherence to a Med diet and the risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality, and an intervention trial demonstrated that the Med diet was more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and lowering the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in overweight individuals. Prior studies did not focus on stroke or stroke-related mortality.

This epidemiological study tracked 74,886 women aged 38 to 63, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who are participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study involving 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. Over six periods from 1984 to 2004, the authors calculated an aMed diet score from self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake over the preceding year. More than 95% of nurses maintained their participation throughout the 20-year period. FFQs underwent validation studies. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were verified through medical or hospital records, autopsy, or death certificates. When records were unavailable, cases were considered "probable" and included, with about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts classified as such. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and postmenopausal hormone use were calculated for each FFQ, and beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed.

To minimize random variation for an individual and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated (by averaging scores from the two preceding years). Adjustments were made for "confounders" (factors that could influence the results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to assess the association between an aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as reflected by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women. Over 20 years of follow-up, 2391 cases of incident CHD, 1763 cases of incident stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (comprising fatal CHD and strokes) were identified. Women in the top aMed quintile had a lower risk of both CHD and stroke compared to those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States of America experienced a severe financial crisis. Unemployment rose, the housing market crashed, and many of America's largest and most important corporations were left in ruins. This recession continues to this day, so we must ask: how did this crisis happen, and how can we prevent it? In short, the financial crisis was caused by greedy and naive political decisions that pressured banks and companies into issuing subprime loans to an immature and underdeveloped financial system. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwrite and repack these mortgages into CDOs and CDSs. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, banks lacked capital reserves and passed this chaos on to the repacked mortgages they had sold and eventually to the rest of the economy.

The financial crisis took root in 1999 during the Clinton administration as the president sought a second term. He relaxed lending restrictions to boost his popularity, which set the stage for the subprime crisis seven years later. Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999 that Fannie Mae, the nation's largest mortgage underwriter, faced pressure from the Clinton administration to expand mortgage loans to low and moderate-income people and from shareholders to maintain profit growth. Holmes also warned of the consequences: "But the government-subsidized corporation may face trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s." As mentioned earlier, and as Holmes foresaw, this ill-advised lending led to the economic meltdown.

Several factors combined to push the economy into a tailspin, one of which was the complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs) were extensively used in the years leading up to the crisis, further intertwining various sectors of the economy with the housing market. This led to overleveraging by U.S. households and financial markets, making them extremely vulnerable to even minor price changes. The housing bubble burst, and financial institutions that had purchased these mortgage-backed securities were severely impacted. The top five U.S. investment banks collectively reported $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts in 2007, which was around 30% of the U.S. GDP. Ultimately, Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch were sold at bargain prices, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subject to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie had $5 trillion in mortgage debt and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition. That part in your story where you unfurl your author's wings and take flight, leaving readers astounded by your captivating prose. Or the section where readers fall asleep or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name. Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in a fun way.

Exposition is not your ally.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still finds herself in long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much. Exposition is the little devil on your shoulder whispering to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of each character's childhood).

Exposition means conveying information to the audience, typically in straightforward prose. In films, exposition happens when one character tells another a lengthy information dump, like "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner." In fiction, the author is the one doing the telling.

Here's an example. While reading a story, you might be told that the heroine met her beloved at a certain place and time, that they were married in a grand way, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes. You wouldn't expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both characters only have two lines of dialogue each. You would expect the author to spend time on the husband's character, demonstrating through his speech and manner his deep love for his wife, and to show, in both big and small ways, how much his presence enriched her life (especially if the story were to later confirm this). A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally invested in his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, the depth of their bond, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through his eyes, and so on. You would mourn his death with her, and thus become more connected to the heroine herself.

In summary, you would expect some substance to the bare bones of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that substance. (*Looks at metaphor, sighs, presses on*) Sometimes it's tempting to rush through certain details.
